{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513064"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:04:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:04:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11998"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11998"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.35,0.2,0.07,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4588"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112902"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4588"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11998"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94939"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"256"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1266"},{"type":"tags","id":"1267"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9084"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6908"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7030"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26783"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43882"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44789"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46340"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112902"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old man presents with a two week history of worsening painless jaundice. Over the last month he has had a decreased appetite and fatigue. He also mentioned that his urine appears darker in colour. His medical history includes chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, for which he requires home oxygen. He also has benign prostatic hyperplasia, diagnosed four years ago which is currently being treated with tamsulosin. He underwent a Roux-en-Y gastric bypass surgery for severe obesity 10 years ago. On physical examination he has yellow sclera and conjunctival pallor. Liver function tests and a three-phase abdominal CT scan are arranged (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP)","Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)","Whole body PET-scan","Diagnostic laparoscopy","Abdominal ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture suggests obstructive jaundice and this is confirmed on the liver function tests. It is also important to remember that painless jaundice in an older man is due to pancreatic cancer until proven otherwise. The CT scan shows a mass in the head of the pancreas, making pancreatic cancer the most likely diagnosis. This investigation has a diagnostic accuracy of 89%. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis has been established and the next step must be to consider how this problem is going to be managed. He is a poor surgical risk and the aim of management must be on how to relieve his jaundice. In most instances \u003Cstrong\u003EERCP\u003C/strong\u003E is the preferred next step, considering the insertion of a biliary stent. However due to the patient\u0027s gastric bypass history, ERCP is not going to be feasible. Gastric bypass is a relative contraindication of ERCP, due to the anatomical variation leading to difficulty in accessing the duodenal limb (Roux-en-Y bypass). One possible approach might be laparoscopic cannulation of the distal gastric pouch and gaining access to the common bile duct by this route. However, a most practical solution is an \u003Cstrong\u003EMRCP. \u003C/strong\u003EThis is a non-invasive procedure and will provide an accurate picture of the biliary tree. A decision can then be made as to how best deal with the obstruction. Considering the size of the lesion and the patient\u0027s co-morbidities, it is unlikely that surgical resection is going to be considered and some form of biliary drainage will be needed. A detailed outline of the biliary system by MRCP will help determine the practicalities of a percutaneous stent insertion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhole body PET scan\u003C/strong\u003E might be done to stage the cancer and reveal any possible metastases, however MRCP/ERCP should be prioritised to properly assess the biliary system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnostic laparoscopy \u003C/strong\u003Eis not a common surgery used in diagnosing pancreatic cancer. It is more commonly done in patients with stomach carcinoma for the risk of peritoneal metastases. Moreover in a 65-year-old patient with significant co-morbidities such as this one, non-invasive measures will be preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal ultrasound \u003C/strong\u003Eis unlikely to give additional information that the CT-scan has not already provide.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Three-phase CT is the most preferred diagnostic tool for pancreatic cancer.","MRCP is a non-invasive alternative to ERCP, especially in patients with altered anatomy such as post-gastric bypass.","Painless jaundice in an older patient is highly suggestive of pancreatic cancer."],"references":["Hanada K, Minami T, Shimizu A, Fukuhara M, Yano S, Sasaki K, Koda M, Sugiyama K, Yonehara S, Yanagisawa A. Roles of ERCP in the Early Diagnosis of Pancreatic Cancer. Diagnostics (Basel). 2019 Mar 7;9(1):30. doi: 10.3390/diagnostics9010030. PMID: 30866585; PMCID: PMC6468574. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30866585/","Nayman A, \u00d6zbek O, Erol S, Karaku\u015f H, Kaya HE. Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography evaluation of intrahepatic bile duct variations with updated classification. Diagn Interv Radiol. 2016 Nov-Dec;22(6):489-494. doi: 10.5152/dir.2016.16051. PMID: 27538048; PMCID: PMC5098941. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5098941/","Knipe H, Worsley, C. Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography. Radiopaedia. 2022. Accessed on 07 Sep 2022. Available via: https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-35490","Stoop TF, Javed AA, Oba A, et al. Pancreatic cancer. Lancet 2025; 405:1182-202."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94939"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11998"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17142"},{"type":"media","id":"17143"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17142"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ad1c7bcd-3041-44ed-946e-4ae409faa013.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ad1c7bcd-3041-44ed-946e-4ae409faa013.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":178}},{"type":"media","id":"17143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17143"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2e38143b-8aac-4913-bdff-0eaa8c8a2435.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2e38143b-8aac-4913-bdff-0eaa8c8a2435.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":658,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94939"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-07T17:54:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-0